\subsection{Nominal color coding}
Slide 65, meme boys vs girls.\\
Colori difficili da comunicare, meglio attenersi a nomi più generici per il color coding, meglio nomi più espliciti. N.B.: anche l'ambiente (es. eschimesi) influenza il range di colori su cui si trovano nomi per le sfumature.
\subsubsection{Norme}
Slide 84.\\
• Color perception is relative hence we should use just 6 to 10 colors for coding which should be distinct and memorable.
•Syntactic
• Color-coded objects should not be very small
• Large areas: low saturation
• Small areas: high saturation
• Small regions should have luminance contrast 
• Adjacent regions should not differ only in the blue component. 
• Avoid highly-saturated highly-bright in spectrally extreme hues (e.g.,blue-red, yellow-purple)
• The color of a patch affects its perceived area. 
• A method for reducing contrast effects is to place a thin white or black border around the color-coded object.• Semantic
• Use cultural conventions, if possible

\subsection{Quantitative color coding}
Slide 85-98.\\
Color can be also used in a quantitative fashion, i.e. to convey
information about ordered data set. We can distinguish here among
ordinal, interval and ratio color coding.
- In Ordinal coding the data values are in some way ordered, i.e.,
the data values can be put into a sequence, but no distance is
defined between data values.
- In interval (quantitative) coding data one can define a distance
between two data values, but the zero point is arbitrary.
- In Ratio coding a zero point is also defined.
• The data -> the color scale can be Discrete/Continuous
Trumbo's principles seem important in generating and evaluating an ordinal color scale:
- Principle I (Order). If the data are ordered, then the colors chosen to represent them should be perceived as preserving that order. - Principle II (Separation). Important differences in data values should be represented by colors clearly perceived as different.

